text=:Category: SignLanguage%0a:Expansion: Brain Adaptation%0a:Author: tylerd%0a:Original: [[Articles.SignVsSpokenLanguageInTheBrain|SignVsSpokenLanguageInTheBrain]] %0a:OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.dhrutik|dhrutik]]%0a:Section: C%0a:Completed: 07.05.2021 - 15:45%0a:Status: complete%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%0a[[#history]]%0a#foxbegin 210511-024216-240590#%0a* [-10.05.2021 - 19:42-] || TA_lili marked as complete%0a#foxend 210511-024216-240590#%0a[[#historyend]]%0a%0a%25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%0a[[#comments]]%0a%0a[[#commentsend]]%0a%0a----%0a----%0a!!%0a%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aThis is a very cool phenomenon that occurs when perceiving sign language. Really impressive that the brain is able to adapt for its abilities and become an effective processing unit in all sorts of scenarios. This inspired me to look into changes in how the brain processes information after undergoing a trauma or if there is a difference from birth. It turns out that the brain wants to be the most effective unit it can be and will shift processes based on the abilities of the human it is attached to. For example, those who are visually impaired from an early age will have brains that are more effective auditory processing units. Additionally, this repurposing is very uniform. Studies of many blind people's brains use the region typically associated with vision (the visual cortex) for auditory processing and motion detection and will be able to pinpoint where a sound comes from.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a(:Category:)%0a(:GradedBy: TA_lili:)
